Being fairly deep and clear with abundant offshore structure,Alexander is normally a "tough" lake with fishing success best on overcast days orat night. Angling success is likely to remain high for 1 to 3 pound walleyesduring the next few years due to the presence of a strong 1992 year class. Trophyindividuals in excess of 10 pounds are also present. Northern pike abundance was within the normal range when compared to lakessimilar to Alexander. Maintaining northern pike at normal levels ensures a healthyfish community. Northerns grow fast and good numbers of fish exceeding 24 inchesin length were present in 1994 assessments. Prior surveys have documented fish inexcess of 20 pounds. Due to fast growth rates and fairly low abundance, trophymanagement is a possibility. Pike in Alexander would probably respond well to ahigh minimum size length limit. At this time, we recommend anglers release allnorthern pike over 24 inches. This should help preserve the quality aspect of thepopulation. Directed sampling scheduled for the spring of 1995 should provideadditional information regarding population size and structure. Both largemouth and smallmouth bass are present in good numbers makingAlexander a popular lake with tournament anglers and fishing clubs. Largemouth andsmallmouth in excess of 5 pounds are frequently caught. Releasing the majority ofmedium to large size bass of both species should ensure quality angling in thefuture. A muskellunge fishery begun in 1988 is now producing legal size (> 40") fish. Fish in the 30 inch range should be well represented in the population as well. Lake Alexander has excellent trophy potential with its abundant and diverse preybase and is reflected in muskies that are heavy for their length. We recommendthat all muskies be released. Yellow perch abundance declined significantly in 1994 probably due to highsurvival of heavily stocked walleye fingerlings. Hopefully current gaps in thewalleye stocking schedule will allow perch to recover. Yellow perch are extremelyimportant for maintaining good growth rates of gamefish. Northern cisco and white sucker, also important prey fish, appear to bepresent in healthy numbers and provide an additional food source for largepredators. Bluegills tend to be small with few individuals exceeding 7 inches. Blackcrappies are normal in abundance and provide good winter and spring fishing foranglers in the know.

Alexander Lake (DOW# 49-0079; Lake Class 22) is a 2,708-acre lake located near Randall, Minnesota. There are two Minnesota Department of Natural Resources (MNDNR) owned concrete boat ramps on the west and east shore. A township owned gravel boat ramp is located on the south shore. Alexander Lake has 16.26 miles of shoreline and a maximum depth of 64 feet. The lake is primarily managed for Walleye and secondarily for Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, and Muskellunge. The lake was initially surveyed in 1950 and 39 fish sampling surveys or investigations have occurred since then with the most recent prior sampling in 2015 (targeted survey for young of year Walleye). Fall night electrofishing has be completed on an annual or biennial basis since 1994 in Alexander Lake.

Fall night electrofishing was conducted on Alexander to evaluate success of fry stocking. The young of year (YOY) Walleye catch rate was 193.90 fish per hour. This was higher than in 2015 (157.80 fish per hour), and was the fourth highest catch rate since 2007. Historically, high electrofishing catch rates have not corresponded with gill net catches. Mean length of YOY Walleye was 6.12 inches. This was smaller than 2015 (6.35 inches), but similar to past surveys (5.98-7.05 inches).

Lake Alexander is a 2,708-acre lake located near Randall, Minnesota. The lake has 16.26 miles of shoreline, a maximum depth of 64 feet, and a littoral area of 842 acres. The primary management species is Walleye. Secondary management species include Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, and Muskellunge. The Walleye population on Lake Alexander is managed through annual stocking of 2,500,000 fry. This stocking strategy has maintained a population that sustains a very good recreational fishery. Recent documentation of a significant natural year class (2020) when no stocking occurred due to COVID19 shutdowns may lead to future adjustments to stocking strategies to allow assessment of natural reproduction.

Night electrofishing in the fall has been used to evaluate young of the year Walleye abundance from spring fry stocking or natural reproduction since 1994. Fall electrofishing in 2022 was completed on 20 September to assess Walleye fry stocking survival. The catch per hour in two hours of effort at all stations was 8.5 fish per hour. Young of the year Walleye sampled ranged from 5.9 to 7.4 inches in total length and mean length was 6.8 inches. The 2022 fall electrofishing catch rate was the lowest rate observed on Lake Alexander in a fry stocked year. Catch rates in prior fall assessments ranged from 21.4/hour (1997) to 733.1/hour (2007) with a median catch rate of 114.0/hour. Catch rates in the last three fall assessments have been at or below the 1st quartile (34.0/hour). The fall 2020 catch of young of the year Walleye (24.5/hour) was the highest catch rate observed for naturally produced fish. These results indicate further analysis of natural reproduction should be continued by adjusting stocking schedules and continuing fall electrofishing assessments in both stocked and non-stocked years.

Historically, fall electrofishing catch rates of juvenile Walleye have been a good predictor of future year classes in summer gillnet surveys. Analysis of fall electrofishing catches showed that, in general, high fall catch rates have typically corresponded with higher catches in future gillnet surveys. Low fall catch rates, however, do not always signify poor year classes as represented by future gillnet catches. Fall catch rates as low as 21.0/hour have been well represented in future gillnet surveys above the third quartile (2.3/net). Other years with low fall electrofishing catch rates produced significant year classes of more than 1.5/gillnet. In summary, despite low fall electrofishing catches in recent years, future gillnet surveys will provide better clarity on the success of recent fry stockings or natural year classes.

Twenty-two additional Walleye were sampled during the survey ranging from 10.9 to 24.1 inches in total length. Eight yearlings were sampled and averaged 11.6 inches in total length. Three Muskellunge were captured ranging from 21.5 to 33.5 inches. All three fish retained PIT tags applied in previous assessments or at time of stocking. Juvenile and adult Yellow Perch were present in good numbers as were Shiner species. Bluegill were abundant at some sites with a few approaching 8 inches. Black Crappie were common and more abundant than in any similar electrofishing efforts performed in the fall, most were 10-12 inches. Largemouth, Smallmouth, and Rock Bass were also common. A few Northern Pike and adult White Suckers were observed. Bullheads were conspicuously absent. A Mottled Sculpin was observed during the survey.

Lake Alexander is a 2,708-acre lake located near Randall, Minnesota. The lake has 16.26 miles of shoreline, a maximum depth of 64 feet, and a littoral area of 842 acres. The primary management species is Walleye. Secondary management species include Northern Pike, Largemouth Bass, Smallmouth Bass, and Muskellunge (MUE). This assessment was directed at evaluating the MUE population. Modern MUE management began in 1988 with a stocking of 850 fingerlings from direct Mississippi River brood stock. Subsequent stockings were primarily from Leech Lake brood stock. Initial stockings were somewhat intermittent, but eventually stocking occurred every other year with any age (fingerling, yearling or adult) fish through 2010. Beginning in 2012 annual stocking began with a preference to utilize yearling or older fish when available at a lower stocking rate to meet population goals. Beginning in 2016, all MUE stocked in Lake Alexander have been injected with PIT (Passive Integrated Transponder) tags. In addition, all untagged MUE captured in assessments of any kind on the lake have been PIT tagged.

A spring MUE assessment was completed in May 3 through 20, 2022 using large-frame trap nets (LTNs) on Lake Alexander to evaluate the MUE population and obtain valuable size structure data on other gamefish species to compare to previous ice-out surveys. The Lake Management Plan goal for MUE is to maintain a population of 400 to 600 adult fish greater than 30 inches, therefore a population estimate was also obtained. Lake Alexander also has a pike regulation that prohibits harvest of fish between 24 and 36 inches in length while allowing one over 36 inches in possession. Twelve LTNs were set in the lake the first day of total ice-out in historical locations. A total of 143 set days were recorded with the twelve nets over a seventeen day period. To increase MUE catch and aid in population estimation, four daytime electrofishing runs were conducted.

A total of 93 MUE greater than 30 inches in total length were captured in LTNs and by electrofishing during the 2022 spring assessment. An additional 18 MUE less than 30 inches were captured, 17 by LTNs and one by electrofishing. Total catch rate of MUE captured in LTNs including recaptures and fish less than 30 inches was 0.69/set day (n=98). Discounting recaptures, large trapnets captured 91 MUE in 143 lifts for a catch rate of 0.64/set day. Catch rates from prior MUE assessments on Lake Alexander have ranged from 0.23/set day (n=20) in 1998 to 6.50/set day (n=260) in 2001. Catch rates from MUE assessments are quite variable based on weather patterns and days required to capture desired numbers of fish. In recent surveys, managers have established a goal to catch at least 100 Muskellunge. Consequently, catch rates are calculated but offer little benefit for making management decisions.

Trapnetting and electrofishing captured 66 unique male and 18 female Muskellunge exceeding 30.0 inches in the 2022 assessment. The ratio of males to females was 3.7:1 which was similar to the last two assessments (2014=3.6:1, 2018=3.8:1). Male MUE ranged from 30.6 to 47.0 inches and averaged 41.1 inches in total length. Females captured ranged from 37.3 to 53.9 inches and averaged 47.7 inches in total length. The percent of females sampled greater than 45 and 50 inches was 78.9% and 26.3% respectively. The percent of females greater than 45 inches had been increasing from 18.2% in 2001 to a high of 85.7% in 2018 as the population matured. The percent of female MUE greater than 45 inches has exceeded the management goal (30%>45") in every survey since 2004. The maximum observed length for females has also increased with the largest individual ever sampled captured in the 2022 assessment (53.9 inches). Females exceeding 50 inches have been captured since 2004 on Lake Alexander. The highest catch of 50+ inch fish occurred in 2014 when 11 were sampled. The presence of fish over 50 inches has made Lake Alexander a destination lake for anglers looking for trophy size fish.

Four daytime electrofishing runs were conducted as an additional method of capture for a population estimate. A total of 12 Muskellunge greater than 30 inches were sampled. Two of the twelve MUE sampled were recaptures. The population estimate of adult Muskellunge over 30 inches for 2022 was 372 fish using the modified Schnabel Estimate. The estimate was slightly below the lake management goal of an adult population between 400 and 500 fish. Population estimates from the last three MUE assessments have been similar, 2014=361, 2018=351, and suggest the population has leveled off. Earlier population estimates in both 2010 (n=642) and 2001 (n=571) were above the management goal while the 2004 estimate of 492 adult fish was within the goal.

Juvenile MUE less than 30 inches were also captured in LTNs (n=15) and in an EF run (n=1). Two juveniles were untagged suggesting potential natural reproduction or tag loss from stocked fish. This is the largest number of juvenile MUE captured in an assessment on Lake Alexander. Previous catches of fish under 30.0 inches ranged from zero in 2014 to 11 in 1996. It is unknown whether this indicates good survival of stocked fish in recent years or that juvenile fish were shallow and vulnerable to capture for some other reason.

Adult MUE were first PIT tagged on Lake Alexander in the 2018 spring assessment. Seventeen MUE, 16 males and 1 female, tagged in 2018 were captured during the 2022 assessment. Length of males at time of tagging ranged from 39.0 to 46.4 inches and averaged 42.0 inches. The amount of growth observed over four growing seasons ranged from -0.5 to 2.8 inches with a mean increment of 1.2 inches. Negative growth for some males was unexpected but may be explained by fin erosion, declining condition of very old individuals, or measurement error due to a variety of factors. It appears growth rates for males slows significantly once they exceed 40 inches although some individuals have attained lengths up to 47 inches in Lake Alexander. The female fish recaptured grew 3.4 inches from 48.1 to 51.5 inches.

Weights were obtained for 10 female and 39 male MUE captured during the 2022 assessment. Compared to 18 females and 64 males weighed in 2014, fish of both sexes weighed slightly less at any given length in 2022. The difference was more noticeable in males than in females. Older fish in the population may account for differences observed. In addition, lower sample sizes in 2022 may account for differences in female condition. In the past, Lake Alexander MUE condition has compared favorably with other well known MUE waters in Minnesota and there are no current concerns. In general, MUE caught by anglers will have a healthy appearance with the exception of some very old males that will appear skinny.

Lake Alexander has a protected slot limit regulation where all Northern Pike (NOP) between 24 and 36 inches must be released. One NOP greater than 36 inches is allowed in the bag of three fish. The intent of the NOP regulation was to increase population size structure quality. The NOP catch in the 2022 spring assessment totaled 449 fish between 10.9 and 35.5 inches in length with a mean length of 21.2 inches. Females ranged from 13.9 to 35.5 inches with a mean length of 21.9 inches. Males averaged 18.9 inches and ranged from 10.9 to 25.0 inches in total length. Percent of all NOP exceeding 24, 30 and 36 inches was 16.7%, 2%, and 0% respectively. Size structure goals specified in the Lake Management Plan call for 50% of the sample to exceed 24 inches and 5% to exceed 30 inches. Surveys following implementation of the slot limit in 2008 and 2010 showed size structure improvement with individuals greater than 24 inches comprising 39% and 68% of the catch respectively. Spring surveys since 2014, however, have failed to meet management goals dropping to 20% in 2014, 27% in 2018, and to 16.7% in 2022. Percent of NOP exceeding 30 inches has met population goals in all surveys since 2010 but declined below goal in 2022. Since 2008, percent of NOP greater than 30 inches has ranged from 2.0% in 2022 to 18.5% in 2010. A potential confounding factor in the last three spring assessments has been late ice-out dates. Assessments in 2014, 2018 and 2022 all began in May. Many NOP captured in 2022 were already spent so sampling may have missed some of the larger individual NOP in the lake. Future spring assessments conducted during a more normal mid-April time frame may provide a better evaluation of the effectiveness of the protected slot limit. Future survey results and public input should determine whether managers keep the slot limit or return to the regular statewide regulation.

Walleye (WAE) are the primary management species on Lake Alexander and were the most abundant gamefish species captured in LTNs. WAE captured in nets were given a left pelvic fin clip in order to keep track of recaptured individuals. A total of 634 unique WAE were captured in 2022, of which 113 were recaptured for a total catch of 747 which is the second highest catch ever recorded. Previous assessments did not keep track of recaptured individuals and total catches ranged from 59 in 2008 to 915 in 2014. The average number of WAE captured in spring assessments since LTNs have been used was 460. WAE captured in 2022 averaged 19.5 inches and ranged from 12.2 to 30.4 inches in total length. Modal length was 17.0-18.0 inches. The 2022 sample was comprised of 204 females, 419 males, and 11 of unknown sex. Females averaged 22.6 inches and ranged from 15.0 to 30.4 inches in total length. Males ranged from 13.4 to 25.4 inches and averaged 18.2 inches. Due to sampling during spawning, medium and large fish comprised most of the catch. WAE between 16 and 20 inches accounted for 56.5% (n=422) of the sample while an additional 36.1% (n=270) of the fish were more than 20 inches in length.

The WAE gillnet catch (2.87/set) in the Standard Survey conducted in August 2021 was the lowest ever recorded on Lake Alexander. Low gillnet catches occurred despite high fall electrofishing catch rates of young of the year WAE (YWAE) leading up to the 2021 Standard Survey. High catches of WAE in the 2022 MUE assessment suggest the 2021 gillnet catch may have given an inaccurate low estimate of population abundance. Zebra Mussels were first detected in Lake Alexander in 2019 and may be negatively impacting the WAE population. Fall electrofishing YWAE catch rates averaged 213.1/hour and ranged from 81.0 to 733.1/hour from 2001 through 2018. Since 2019, fall electrofishing catch rates of YWAE have been declining, averaging 27.0/hour and ranging from 8.5 to 40.9/hour. It is unknown whether these lower fall catch rates will correspond to weaker year classes in the future. Lake Alexander has been included in a research study to determine the impacts of Zebra Mussels on Walleye recruitment. In the coming years, fish managers and researchers will need to continue to study the impacts of Zebra Mussel infestation on Walleye population dynamics in the lake and determine if different management strategies will need to be employed to maintain Walleye population goals, or whether goals will need to be readjusted.

Spring MUE assessments on Lake Alexander have provided an excellent opportunity to collect additional data on the Black Crappie population. The 2022 assessment sampled 613 crappie between 5.2 and 14.9 inches in length which was the highest catch recorded in a spring assessment. Black Crappie catches have ranged from 16 to 513 fish in past spring assessments. Mean length for the sample in 2022 was 10.2 inches with a modal length of 10 - 11 inches. Netting results suggest that Lake Alexander has a quality Crappie fishery as 65.4% (n=401) of fish captured exceeded ten inches in length and 10.6% (n=65) greater than twelve inches.

High numbers of Bluegill have also been observed in the early spring assessments with the highest catch of 1,686 fish in April 2010. The 2022 Muskellunge assessment netted 533 Bluegill ranging from 3.7 to 8.9 inches in length. Mean length for the 2022 sample was 6.6 inches and modal length 7.0 - 7.5 inches. Bluegill greater than 7.0 and 8.0 inches comprised 42.8% (n=228) and 4.1% (n=22) of the catch respectively. Bluegill greater than 8.0 inches are typically low in LTN catches on Lake Alexander and there appears to be no improving or declining trend in size structure. Anglers can expect to readily find keeper size fish in the 7 inch range with an occasional 8 inch fish in the bag.

Largemouth (n=92) and Smallmouth Bass (n=76) were caught in the 2022 MUE assessment. Largemouth Bass captured ranged from 6.6 to 14.9 inches and averaged 10.2 inches. Smallmouth Bass caught were typically larger, had a mean length of 15.6 inches, and ranged from 10.5 to 19.5 inches in total length.

Other fish species netted in the 2022 Muskellunge assessment included Black Bullhead, Bowfin, Brown Bullhead, Green Sunfish, Hybrid Sunfish, Pumpkinseed, Rock Bass, Shorthead Redhorse, White Sucker, Yellow Bullhead, and Yellow Perch. Rock Bass were the most abundant species captured during the 2022 assessment with 1,472 fish netted.

This survey report is an update from the 2018 survey report. Gill nets were used to sample Walleye, Northern Pike and Yellow Perch. In Lake Alexander, Smallmouth Bass are also sampled effectively with gill nets. Bluegill, Cisco, Largemouth Bass and Black Crappie are usually seen to a lesser extent since they typically occupy different habitat than where gill nets are placed. Fifteen gill nets are used in Lake Alexander and the lake is typically surveyed the last full week of August.

In general, the best way to understand fish sampling data from individual lake surveys is to look at them as a snapshot that estimates the current relative abundance and general size structure of the species discussed. Note that the data are only estimates and intended to provide a qualitative description of the fishery. More telling are data trends over the course of a fish generation (10-20 years). For example, the number of Northern Pike in "Lake X" (expressed as number per gill net) rising steadily in each survey from 2000 to 2020 would be much more telling than a single survey-year showing a major catch increase or decrease. Little Falls Area lakes with the highest recreational value are surveyed every four years; most of these lakes have at least 20-30 years of standardized surveys completed on them.

The 2021 survey of Lake Alexander caught a total 43 Walleyes in the gill nets or 2.9 fish/net. This is about half as many as in 2018 when a total of 92 Walleyes were caught and the catch rate was 6.1 fish/net. The average number of Walleyes caught since 2002 is 5.7 fish/net. Individual sizes ranged from 9-27 inches and the proportion of Walleyes less than 15 inches was as high as it's been since 2002. It's good to see a well-balanced population of Walleyes where adequate numbers of several different size-categories are sampled. However, we will be watching closely to see if the overall low number of Walleyes caught in this survey is just an outlier or a sign of something more concerning.

Walleye fry are stocked annually in Lake Alexander and the current stocking strategy has provided several good years of fishing. Fall electrofishing surveys the past three years however have resulted in fewer young-of-year (juvenile) Walleye caught than we'd like to see. Lower electrofishing catch-rates don't always mean poor survival to catchable size, but our fall electrofishing in 2022 and the next gill net survey in 2024 will hopefully see a rebound in numbers caught.

Northern Pike continue to be present in low numbers which is ideal for other species such as Walleye and Muskellunge. The 2003 special regulation requiring the release of all pike between 24 and 36 inches is showing signs of success in increasing the number of larger pike. Early spring netting surveys have shown higher percentages of pike over 30 inches than before the regulation was enacted.

Yellow Perch, a primary forage species for many game fish, seem to follow an up and down trend in Lake Alexander. Currently, there are adequate numbers of perch to sustain a prey base for Walleyes. Because pike abundance is low, perch abundance has not severely declined as can occur on other lakes where numbers of small pike have risen to nuisance levels.

The Smallmouth Bass population in Lake Alexander remains healthy and we caught a nice range of sizes (5-19 inches). At this time, Smallmouth Bass may be the best quality fishery in the lake.

An early spring Muskellunge survey is planned for 2022. Updated information regarding this species will be available next year. For past Muskellunge netting results and status of the fishery, see the 2018 standard survey.
